5. suis . . . umeris sustineret: cf. Verr. v. 108 collo et cervicibus suis sustinerent, Seu. 39, Dom. 40.

6. collinam: modern editors accept the explanation of G. Wolff [Phil. xvii. 726], ‘Clodius held a reunion of the greatest rascals from each tribe, who promised to work against Milo. This gathering Cicero calls a new Colline tribe, since this was the least reputable of the four city÷tribes3 This seems extrava- gantly far-felched. There is practically no evidence to show that the Colline cnjoyed a worse reputation than the other tribes [Momms. Staatsr. iii. 164. 3] beyond the fact that in the ordo tribuum [Liv. Epit. xx.] it is last of the four. The tribe in which demagogues had most power was the Palatine, Sest. 114. I take the words literally, and suppose that Cicero attributes to Clodius an intention to duplicate the existing Collina.
